@mattupstate A concrete example: for PyGotham, we occasionally create accounts on behalf of invited speakers. In the interest of not sending a randomly generated password in cleartext, we send them a password reset link. Our current workaround for the `MD5(None)` issue is to set the password hash to some value that a legitimate hash will never collide with and generate the reset link based on that. This is roughly equivalent to what you suggest, but it would be convenient if it was not a required step.

The other change ensures that a password reset link cannot be used after the hash with which it was generated has changed. This is not currently the case, and I think it's a necessary step. If someone does currently expect a password reset token to work more than once, they're explicitly weakening the security of their application and should be discouraged / prevented from doing so. That said, it's an important change in behavior, and my main point was that this should make it into the changelog.

