I'm afraid that ``format_date`` is going to be confusing together with Invenio-I18Ns ``datetimeformat`` and ``dateformat``. See [Flask-BabelEx](https://github.com/mrjoes/flask-babelex/blob/master/flask_babelex/__init__.py#L113-L116). The I18N functions should normally be used for date/time formatting when presenting them to the user. This Jinja filter is useful in the cases where you do not need to localise a date (e.g. the highwire press tags).

Perhaps we can change it to ``format_arrow`` as the function will format arrow-objects:

```python
def format_arrow(value, format_string):
    """Format an arrow datetime object.

    .. note::
        Do not use this filter to format date/times presented to an enduser. Instead use ``datetimeformat`` or ``dateformat`` from Invenio-I18N.
    """
    assert isinstance(value, arrow)
    return value.format(format_string)

def to_arrow(value):
    return arrow.get(value)
```

Then the usage in the Jinja template becomes:

```jinja
{{ publication_date|to_arrow|format_arrow('YYYY/MM/DD')}}
```

or alternatively we can avoid the filter ``format_arrow`` filter:

```jinja
{% set higwire_pubdate = publication_date|to_arrow %}
{{ higwire_pubdate.format('YYYY/MM/DD') }}
```

