@parity3 A nursery and a queue seems like a lot of machinery to -- basically reimplement a simple `Lock`? I don't think it gives you any benefits over that? (Except that it allows you to add some buffering, but I don't think buffering is useful here.)

It's an interesting idea to tell the stream how to serialize messages, so that (using my example from above) it could effectively move the call to `_sansio_conn.encode_message` inside its internal `Lock`. But I think this mixes layers in a way that will cause awkwardness: what if you need to pass extra arguments to the encode function, what if you want multiple encode functions for different messages types, what if the encode function needs to be async, etc. etc. Doing the locking by hand isn't hard; the hard part is doing something sensible for people who don't realize there's a problem to worry about.

Also, something to keep in mind is that `Stream` is an abstract interface with multiple implementations (`SocketStream`, `SSLStream`, `StapledStream`, memory streams for testing, etc.), so even if we do think there's value in having a reusable "serialize a message and then send it on a `Stream` with appropriate locking" abstraction, it's probably best implemented as a single implementation that can be wrapped around any `Stream`, rather than something that has to be redone inside each `Stream` implementation.

Hi @CFAndy 

Indeed, out of the box, the way the uri resolving is performed does not allow such URI format. Currently, there is a way of registering a new decoder to deal with such URI, but it implies that all the required resources are loaded first in the same `ResourceSet` (the resource auto-load current implementation cannot handle to auto-load it). 
Do you need to only deserialize data or to also serialize them back with the same URI format (meaning that each `Resource` should have a special UUID)?

Also, is the URI used to load the resource `copy://UUID/path/to/file` or simply `path/to/file`?

Regarding your 'constraints' the solution could be either a dedicated URI decoder or a dedicated `Resource` with a special URI (but the resource UUID could be an issue later, it depends on so many parameters).

As example, here is the code I used to deal with such `URI`, considering that all the resources (`a.xmi` and `b.xmi`) would have been loaded first using their path as URI:

```python
from  pyecore.resource import Resource

class SpecialDecoder(object):
    @staticmethod
    def remove_begining(path):
        path = path.replace('copy://', '')
        path = '/'.join(path.split('/')[1:])
        return path

    @classmethod
    def can_resolve(self, path, from_resource):
        if not path.startswith('copy://'):
            return False
        path = self.remove_begining(path)
        return from_resource.resource_set.can_resolve(path, from_resource)  # we use the resource set decoder

    @classmethod
    def resolve(cls, path, from_resource):
        path = cls.remove_begining(path)
        return from_resource.resource_set.resolve(path, from_resource)  # we use the resource set decoder


Resource._decoders.insert(0, CopyDecoder)  # we register the new decoder as first in the _decoders list
```
